        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Content marketing</strong> is a strategic marketing approach that attracts customers through useful content — articles, videos, guides, podcasts, and case studies — rather than through interruptive advertising. Companies that blog regularly generate <strong>67% more leads per month</strong> than those that do not. Content marketing costs 62% less than outbound and generates 3x more leads over time.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Lead lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">67% (regular blogging)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost vs outbound</div>
            <div class="tms-value">62% less, 3x leads</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Modern buyers research before they engage. They consume 3 to 7 content pieces before contacting a vendor, and 42% of internet users run ad blockers. Content marketing is how you show up in that research phase — and how you keep showing up years after publish.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is content marketing?</h2>
        <p>Content marketing is the discipline of attracting, engaging, and retaining customers by publishing useful content instead of running interruptive ads. Instead of pushing sales messages, you distribute articles, videos, guides, and materials addressing audience problems.</p>
        <p>The category covers everything from a solo founder's LinkedIn posts to a Fortune 500 media brand. What ties them together is intent: content marketing exists to build trust and drive demand before a sale, not to close during it.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why buyers reward it</div>
          <p><strong>70 to 80% of buyers</strong> conduct online research before contacting vendors. <strong>42% of internet users</strong> run ad blockers. Trust built through content precedes sales conversations — and outlasts them.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why content marketing matters</h2>
        <p>Five reasons content marketing outperforms paid channels over the long run:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Compounding traffic.</strong> A blog post published today keeps ranking and driving traffic for years. Ads stop the moment budget stops.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower cost per lead.</strong> Content marketing costs 62% less than outbound marketing while generating 3x more leads.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust before contact.</strong> Buyers pre-qualify vendors through content. By the time they book a demo, they already trust you.</li>
          <li><strong>SEO moat.</strong> Well-structured content builds <a href="/glossary/topical-authority/">topical authority</a> — a moat competitors cannot outbid you on.</li>
          <li><strong>Reusable across channels.</strong> One pillar article feeds newsletter, LinkedIn, video, sales enablement, and paid social.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How content marketing works</h2>
        <p>Every content marketing program runs the same loop: strategy, production, distribution, measurement.</p>
        <h3>Strategy</h3>
        <p>Define business goals, buyer personas, and the content mix that maps to each funnel stage. This is where <a href="/glossary/content-strategy/">content strategy</a> lives.</p>
        <h3>Production</h3>
        <p>Research, brief, write, edit, design, publish. The production engine is where 90% of programs succeed or fail — usually on velocity.</p>
        <h3>Distribution</h3>
        <p>Publish is the middle of the workflow, not the end. Distribute through SEO, email, social, syndication, partnerships, and paid amplification.</p>
        <h3>Measurement</h3>
        <p>Track traffic, engagement, leads, and revenue attribution. Feed learnings back into strategy every quarter.</p>

