              <tr><td><strong>Infographics</strong></td><td>Sharing + backlinks</td><td>Data visualizations</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Newsletters</strong></td><td>Retention + nurture</td><td>Weekly industry roundups</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Webinars</strong></td><td>Lead generation + education</td><td>Workshops, live Q&amp;A</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content marketing examples</h2>
        <h3>1. SaaS blog — 3.5x traffic from publishing volume</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS grew from 4 posts/month to 20 posts/month over one quarter using theStacc. Six months in, organic traffic was 3.5x baseline — matching HubSpot's benchmark that businesses publishing 16+ posts monthly get 3.5x more traffic than those publishing 0 to 4.</p>
        <h3>2. Local service — case-study library</h3>
        <p>A residential solar installer published one case study per install for 18 months. The library now drives 60% of inbound leads because prospects self-qualify against a project close to their own.</p>
        <h3>3. Ecommerce — buying-guide hub</h3>
        <p>A DTC skincare brand built a hub of ingredient buying guides. Each guide targets a specific commercial keyword. Together they capture 200,000+ monthly visits and 8% of first-time purchases.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content marketing vs content strategy — which is which</h2>
        <p>People conflate them, but the split matters for accountability.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content marketing (execution)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The doing — research, write, publish, distribute</li>
              <li>Owned by editorial + growth teams</li>
              <li>Measured on traffic, leads, revenue</li>
              <li>Weekly cadence</li>
              <li>Output is content shipped</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/content-strategy/">Content strategy</a> (blueprint)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The plan — what, whom, when, why</li>
              <li>Owned by content leader or CMO</li>
              <li>Measured on strategic alignment</li>
              <li>Quarterly cadence</li>
              <li>Output is a documented roadmap</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 content marketing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define one business outcome per program.</strong> Traffic, leads, pipeline, retention. Pick one primary. Everything else is secondary.</li>
          <li><strong>Build buyer personas with specific pain points.</strong> Personas without pain are useless. Interview real customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Map content across awareness, consideration, decision.</strong> Every funnel stage needs coverage or the pipeline leaks.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritize depth over volume.</strong> 2 to 4 excellent articles per month beats 30 shallow ones — but at scale, quantity matters too.</li>
          <li><strong>Distribute deliberately.</strong> Publish is 20% of the work. The other 80% is getting it in front of the right people.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure business impact, not vanity.</strong> Traffic without leads is a hobby. Track conversion rates by content asset.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh at 12-month intervals.</strong> The best-performing content in your library is 12 to 24 months old. Refreshing beats rewriting.</li>
          <li><strong>Own your distribution channels.</strong> Email list + SEO + one social channel you fully control. Algorithms change; owned channels do not.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — treating content as a project, not a system</div>
          <p>Programs that ship 40 articles in Q1 and 4 in Q2 do not compound. Consistency beats intensity. A content marketing engine that ships 8 to 12 pieces per month for 24 months outperforms a 100-piece burst every time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content marketing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Publishing without a strategy.</strong> Random posts do not build authority. Every piece needs a role.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring SEO.</strong> If Google cannot find it, only your existing audience will.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping distribution.</strong> "Publish and pray" is the most common failure mode.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing trends instead of evergreen.</strong> Evergreen posts compound. Trending posts spike then die.</li>
          <li><strong>Not measuring past traffic.</strong> Traffic that does not convert is a resume line, not a business result.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc runs your content marketing engine</h2>
        <p>theStacc replaces the freelance stack with one managed engine: research, brief, write, edit, publish, and refresh. Every article ships against a validated keyword, distributed into your CMS, and tracked in your dashboard. From strategy to publish, one team, one subscription.</p>

